Food debt to European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries of the euro area, inflation was higher than expected in November - after 2.6% in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1% was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have been based on only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
In contrast to the US, British, and Canadian central bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the central rate, and the reduction in interest rates would, in their opinion, favour the rise in raw materials prices and the slight fall in unemployment.
The ECB is trying to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the twilight mill: it is necessary to "cancel" inflation in order to exclude the need for action later.
At 3.3 percent in November, the inflation rate in Germany reached a 12-year record level; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The increase in food and energy prices was responsible for the rise in inflation in the euro area.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and the soybean price also reached a record level since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in food oil and milk products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil increased by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1% to 2.5% in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9% in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1%.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
