Many places are saved on disinfectants
More than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to an inappropriate treatment of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overlay of beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the containment of infections, says the leading doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many places are also saved in the case of disinfectants.
In the traumatology department of the János hospital, an MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The bacterium resistant to antibiotics was found in a male patient who was admitted to the hospital after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured person of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not yet be carried out because of the bacterium that is still in the patient's body.
By 10 December this year, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System from hospitals in 1094, according to the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Centre, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals, but the dark rate is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacillin, Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about one third of the people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, almond inflammation, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well-treatable.
However, if the means are used too high or incorrectly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant, which are rapidly spread in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
These bacteria may cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis, especially in patients with a weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in the elderly or low body weight patients.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the day-to-day disease.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulashi - MRSA alone does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistance to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the care staff carry rubber gloves and masks at the supply, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - said Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, the patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoided, but the current conditions and circumstances would be unfavourable for the control of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant disease, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and old-age homes, the hospital should examine the patients who have been delivered and immediately isolate MRSA infected.
However, in the Hungarian hospitals, the microbiological sampling is not used as often.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this investigation on the part of the State Health Fund.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, the medical director of the epidemiology centre.
There are strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine on the part of the European Union, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotics therapy should be targeted, that is, microbiological studies are necessary to ensure that resistance to the drug cannot be established, but this directive is not always respected by hospitals.
Among the outpatient, or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even more rare, says Karolina Böröcz.
is saved in the disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transferred from one patient to another by the care staff.
This is why hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient in the home hospitals.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are close to each other, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz further points out, unfortunately, in the less well-placed hospitals it is even possible to save for disinfectants, there are few carers, many patients - all factors that directly favour the development of infections.
Such infections are shown to be much less common there, or can be stopped the further spread of the pathogen where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
To control MRSA infections causes enormous costs to health insurance, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment in the government programme, has been recorded.
The first signs show that the programme is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England has fallen.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals to be one of its priorities.
