Fodor and the six Hungarian percentage
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by Ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the post-2012 emission reduction measures, that is, after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
A major debate is currently taking place between industrial and developing countries.
The US has already indicated that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be ready to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue of the conference is whether the developed countries are prepared to support developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on support for developing countries has also been reached.
The adaptation fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, expected at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as shown in the Piac és Profit.
Hungary's six percent
Minister for the Environment Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection measures and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by 1990 values), whether the "post-2012" agreement is successful or not. The Union would even be ready to work for a 30% reduction, if other major developed countries in the world, or developing countries, are also ready to meet their obligations in a strong and responsible manner.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, while the EU, with its 15 Member States at the time, had already committed itself to a minus of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to the years 1985-87 - a target that the country will fully meet, as shown in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The deployment is high on Bali - at least the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would not come into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which also has been highlighted by the IPCC, the international UN Scientific Climate Change Committee, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in its recent report.
This would delay the emission reduction, and the increase in the average temperature of the earth by more than 2 ° C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would have very serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army is on YouTube
British Army units have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special Forces stationed in Afghanistan have been charging videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The miniaturcameras that are mounted on helmets are checked at the airbase in Kandahar and then sent to London where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defence headquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos of Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the international peace forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Use in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of foreign operations.
This kind of propaganda was almost free of charge compared to traditional television advertising, according to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message in themselves, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur recordings, which, in addition to the carefully worked, censorship images, also create on the network - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are spoken at the most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, many videos were already in use on the platform of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, but this "genus" has only recently been discovered by the British.
The Americans, however, are advertising in a slightly different way, namely with the free-download shooting game "America's Army," in which the player can slip into the body of the soldier in the context of a more or less life-consuming simulation.
