Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases State Risk
According to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August, with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary," have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things, that, in the context of the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "intensification of the existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy populations in Hungary, which could lead to violent ethnic conflicts even in the short term."
The main reason for this was the Hungarian Guard's strategy, which is probably aimed at provocation of such a conflict, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure by the political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary contrast."
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, promote extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent conflicts.
The research institute also considers that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the national and foreign media, "significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, in particular as regards confidence in stability and democratic maturity."
We remember: since autumn 2006, the reorganisation of radical and extremely right-wing groups in Hungary has been on the rise, so that since summer 2007 several organisations known as the "national self-defence association" have been established.
"These groups are common that they define themselves as a civil organisation, while they are openly boasting to prepare their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (civil protection, state defence, order prevention), calling for the insuitability of the police, the army, or the state itself," they said.
And further: all this is done according to that method, which tries to cover various political aspirations, based on the political and party detentions of the population, as a bourgeois initiative.
So the emphasis on civil character and the form of association is not just about circumventing legal barriers that could appear in the course of the registration to the court - it is a political strategy at the same time.
The analysis shows that the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-enhancing factor in relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, so some of the ultranationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as the confirmation of its own anti-Hungary policy.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region "- it was said.
