Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to carry out the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector that is essential for the continuation of the scientific work on the station.
A bold exit that, due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools made by astronauts to carry out the repair, has achieved several records.
The problem occurred on Wednesday, when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the space ferry Discovery, a large cylindrical part, which is soon to take up the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module laboratories.
But you have to be able to supply them with power.
The second task of the crew was to implement a 17.5 ton module for the generation of electricity through solar collectors, which was already on the ISS, in order to bring it into its final position.
After she had moved it, the crew made the restructuring of the solar panels of the module, the range of which is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors that can be seen as accordion was damaged by a clamp-in cable on a length of about one meter.
The restructuring was stopped in order not to damage the collector any more.
The astronauts, who were originally to leave the space ferry Discovery for one control course and then repair another solar collector, whose rotation system was defective, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around at the end of the 30-metre remote-controlled arm of the space ferry that had been installed at the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA's best space walkers.
Large, resistant, very clever, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old trained doctor was therefore selected to operate the injured solar collector.
After he had carefully examined the damage, he severed the faulty cable and fixed some kind of rail on the damaged site.
He was supported by a second space walker, who remained close to the lock, and, from inside, from the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini-hockey bat, wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric blow on the solar collectors that generate several hundred volts, had the astronauts on board the station designed and built.
When the action was finished, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector had completely folded before he counted his tools and returned to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day's relaxation before today seven astronauts returned to the space ferry Discovery to start the return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
