A heavy memory
After being treated confidentially for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are located at a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, have not been seen until now, except with a humanitarian intention, that is, individual and name-related, that is to say to ask a former victim or his family.
The 11 states responsible for their administration - including Germany, France, Israel and the US - agreed in May 2006 to make them available to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Healthy information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable research to be carried out, in particular through the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of forced workers, Reto Masters, the head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, have been opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the delicate nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The inmates' lists of the concentration camps or the arrest orders issued by the Gestapo had been brought together for a practical reason after the war: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and to provide them with possibly evidence of their arrest in order to pave their way to their compensation.
Even today, in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent, tens of thousands of personal requests are processed.
However, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
It is not possible to expect anything fundamental new in these documents, but it was stated in 2006 that Fr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Centre for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin.
