The harmonised consumer price index (CPI) increased by five-tenth in November and is now 4.1%.
The indicator used by Eurostat to assess the inflation rate within the European Union provides the average price trend in Spain in November.
Its publication is in line with the principles of Eurostat and the European Central Bank (ECB), which seek to compare local and quality to US products by providing the data.
The forecast for the indicator can be prepared in advance by applying the same approach as the harmonised consumer price index, but at the same time using various other statistical modelling methods to estimate the information not available at the time of calculation.
However, the Spanish Statistical Office (INE) warned that the pre-determined indicator would only serve as a reference value and therefore did not have to be in line with the final result, which will be announced on 14 December.
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) will remain at a relatively high level
