New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute between Ukraine and Russia is in the process of increasing the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe being affected.
The majority of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is very closely observed.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit charges from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two states last year reduced supplies to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be charged more, as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from the neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for the imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit countries in talks," said the Minister of Economic Affairs of Ukraine Anatoli Kinakh of the news agency Reuters.
"The changing prices of natural gas should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments on the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] through Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006 Gazprom reduced supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which was a drastic increase in prices.
Russian gas is a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas supply, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom supplements its own supplies of gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the controls of the pre-trial registers for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body outside.
The recommendation of the Chief Financial Controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought together with the attack on the airport of Glasgow in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish State Health Service had no precise idea of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller investigated personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a ground car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in the Old Bailey in October in a video transmission and was charged with the alleged car bomb attack in the UK.
The State Health Service is expected to carry out controls prior to the appointment of foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorisations to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review pre-criminal records, the Agency does not have the power to obtain this information outside the UK.
The report of the main auditor now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines of the criminal record, which helps employers to control in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these controls in some staff documents, they have not been routinely carried out."
Black said that the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigation guidelines very much before they were appointed, but added: "Our report shows areas in which the system can be improved to ensure that precise information on the number of foreign health workers is available."
BMA Scotland President Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks prior to the appointment of potential NHS staff.
"The report states that the NHS Scotland is working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of them doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the board of directors have problems in identifying those employees who have been suspended for an indefinite period of time.
The investigation continued to establish that established control procedures of NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian were mainly observed.
This includes passport, work permit, and qualification controls.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidelines for pre-employment controls for foreign staff in the NHS.
The Secretary of Health Nicola Sturgeon said, "I was concerned to do this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices in updated guidelines on control investigations prior to the appointment of all employees, including those from abroad, would be reflected next month.
