It's not Warhol's box.
Those who connect the terms Sweden and the wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At present, wood boxes made in Sweden are throwing dark shadows on Warhol's work directory.
A large part of the ninety-four Brillo boxes of the "type Stockholm" listed there are forgeries.
After a few months ago, the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes in 1968, internal research in the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now comes to an alarming result: the six "Brillo-Boxes," which the former museum director Pontus Hultén gave to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably most of the around a hundred more Brillo boxes of the "type Stockholm" that are in the international art market.
The history of the past is encapsulated, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes," painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard cartons of the soap powder "Brillo."
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet 1968 - with Warhol's consent - exhibited hundreds of cardboard glasses: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo-Carton factory.
It was not works of art, it was their examples, just exhibits.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol had given permission to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, but they were not issued in the Moderna Museet.
Time witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes that were then authorized as original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes called "type Stockholm" rightly entered into the art and auction history.
Some of them have made more than $100 000 on auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén has later falsely claimed that it was produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol was dead for three years.
Lars Bystrom, head conservatory at the Moderna Museet, has also examined three of Swedish private property, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were first ground and milled, and then white oil color was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, tells us that the colour was applied directly to the press panel with a paint roll without foundation - it is also not oil, but acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorised by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in his collection as copies / exhibition material."
However, in July the Authentication Board announced that it would follow up the "serious accusations" that are being made in the case of the soap powder boxes.
But since then, you have been there in unbeatable silence.
